05323nam a22009375i 9780813542492DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20042004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135424927 a10.36019/97808135424922doi  a(DE-B1597)530277  a(OCoLC)804665128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a302.2322200aGlobal Currents :bMedia and Technology Now /ced. by Tasha G. Oren, Patrice Petro. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in International Studies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRhetoric about media technology tends to fall into two extreme categories: unequivocal celebration or blanket condemnation. This is particularly true in debate over the clash of values when first world media infiltrate third world audiences. Bringing together the best new work on contemporary media practices, technologies, and policies, the essayists in Global Currents argue that neither of these extreme views accurately represents the role of media technology today. New ways of thinking about film, television, music, and the internet demonstrate that it is not only media technologies that affect the cultures into which they are introduced—it is just as likely that the receiving culture will change the media. Topics covered in the volume include copyright law and surveillance technology, cyber activism in the African Diaspora, transnational monopolies and local television industries, the marketing and consumption of “global music,” “click politics” and the war on Afghanistan, the techno-politics of distance education, artificial intelligence and global legal institutions, and traveling and “squatting” in digital space. Balanced between major theoretical positions and original field research, the selections address the political and cultural meanings that surround and configure new technologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBourdon, Jerome.1 aBourdon, Jérôme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraman, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraman, Sandra.1 aCiecko, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiecko, Anne.1 aEverett, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverett, Anna.1 aFoner, Lenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoner, Lenny.1 aJones, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Steve.1 aLarkin, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarkin, Brian.1 aMiller, Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Toby.1 aOhmer, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhmer, Susan.1 aOren, Tasha G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOren, Tasha G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetro, Patrice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSands, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSands, Peter.1 aSreberny, Annabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSreberny, Annabelle.1 aTaylor, Timothy D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Timothy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354249240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97808135424924